# Secrets & Certificates (Demo Rules)

## Secrets handling (no secret manager)
- Secrets are created by:
  1) executing `oc` commands from README instructions, OR
  2) running `deploy.sh` which reads secret data from `.env`.

## Demo secrets in GitOps
- Some demo secrets with placeholder/demo values are committed to GitOps for convenience.
- These MUST include a comment header indicating they are demo values:
  ```yaml
  # ⚠️ DEMO VALUES ONLY - Replace for production use
  # Generate new values: <command to generate>
  ```
- Demo secrets in this repo:
  - `gitops/step-03-enterprise-projects/base/auth/htpasswd-secret.yaml`
  - `gitops/step-03-enterprise-projects/base/minio/credentials-secret.yaml`
  - `gitops/step-04-model-registry/base/database/credentials-secret.yaml`
  - `gitops/step-02-rhoai/base/rhoai-operator/maas-postgres-secret.yaml`
  - `gitops/step-08-model-evaluation/base/evalhub/postgresql-secret.yaml`
  - `gitops/step-10-mcp-integration/base/postgresql/credentials-secret.yaml`

## Never commit real secrets
- Do not commit production secret values.
- For real deployments, replace demo secrets via:
  - External Secrets Operator
  - Sealed Secrets
  - `oc create secret` commands documented in README

## Self-signed certificates
- It is acceptable to bypass TLS verification:
  - `oc --insecure-skip-tls-verify=true ...`
  - `curl -k ...`
- Document where/why TLS is bypassed in README so users aren't surprised.

## ODH managed label gotcha

Do NOT add `opendatahub.io/managed: "true"` to secrets in GitOps manifests. The ODH model controller watches for this label and deletes secrets it didn't create. This causes an infinite create-delete loop when ArgoCD manages the secret.

Affected: `storage-config` secret in `gitops/step-03-enterprise-projects/base/`.

## Security posture awareness (demo context)

This demo intentionally relaxes some security best practices for simplicity.
Document these relaxations explicitly rather than silently accepting them.

Informed by [gitops-manifest-validator security posture analysis](https://github.com/redhat-et/gitops-manifest-validator/tree/main/skills/analyzing-kubernetes-security-posture).

### What we accept for the demo
- Self-signed certs with TLS verification bypassed
- Demo-value secrets committed to GitOps (with `DEMO VALUES ONLY` header)
- `cluster-admin` RBAC for ArgoCD application controller
- No NetworkPolicies (except where operators create them)
- Secrets in env vars for database passwords (MinIO, MariaDB, PostgreSQL)

### What we do NOT accept even for the demo
- Real credentials committed to git (always use `.env` + `load_env`)
- `privileged: true` on any workload container
- `hostPath` volume mounts
- Docker/containerd socket mounts
- Wildcard RBAC (`*` verbs on `*` resources) outside of ArgoCD

OCP 4.20 enforces [Pod Security Admission](https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/openshift_container_platform/4.20/html/authentication_and_authorization/understanding-and-managing-pod-security-admission)
at the namespace level (`restricted` by default). Most of the "do NOT accept" items above
are already blocked by the cluster. This list documents our intent, not just enforcement.

### When adding new secrets to manifests
- Use `envFrom.secretRef` or `env.valueFrom.secretKeyRef` (not inline `env.value`)
- Add the `DEMO VALUES ONLY` comment header if committing placeholder values
- Document the secret's purpose in the step README

## Environment file
- Template: `env.example` (no leading dot for visibility)
- User copy: `.env` (gitignored)
- Load pattern: `deploy.sh` sources `.env` via `lib.sh:load_env()`
